  <graph edgedefault="undirected">
    <node id="JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX is a database index on the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, designed to improve query performance by indexing the DEPARTMENT_ID column. It uses a default B-tree structure with NOLOGGING, NOCOMPRESS, and NOPARALLEL options to optimize maintenance and query efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912551</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.JOB_HISTORY">
      <data key="d0">HR.JOB_HISTORY</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.JOB_HISTORY is a database table within the HR schema that stores detailed historical employment records for employees. It captures job assignments over time, including job roles, department assignments, and time periods, to track career progression, organizational changes, and employee tenure. The table is used for various purposes such as analyzing job transitions, reporting, auditing, and HR analytics. To ensure data integrity and validity of chronological job periods, HR.JOB_HISTORY enforces constraints through primary keys, foreign keys, and check constraints.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912868</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPARTMENT_ID">
      <data key="d0">DEPARTMENT_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPARTMENT_ID is a numeric identifier (NUMBER(4)) that uniquely represents each department within an organization. It serves as the primary key column in the HR.DEPARTMENTS table, ensuring the unique identification of every department. In the HR.EMPLOYEES table, DEPARTMENT_ID functions as a column that typically acts as a foreign key referencing the HR.DEPARTMENTS table, thereby associating employees with their respective departments. This column is also used as the key for the HR.EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX index. Additionally, DEPARTMENT_ID appears in the JOB_HISTORY table as a nullable foreign key attribute, linking each job history record to the corresponding department in the HR.DEPARTMENTS table. Overall, DEPARTMENT_ID plays a crucial role in maintaining the organizational structure and data integrity by connecting employees and their job histories to the appropriate departments.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913423</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPARTMENTS is a database table containing department information, referenced by HR.EMPLOYEES to assign employees to valid departments.&lt;SEP&gt;DEPARTMENTS is a database table that stores department information, referenced by the DEPARTMENT_ID column in JOB_HISTORY.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912623</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOLOGGING">
      <data key="d0">NOLOGGING</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">NOLOGGING is a database operation mode and storage parameter primarily used during the creation and maintenance of indexes, such as the B-tree indexes LOC_CITY_IX, LOC_COUNTRY_IX, hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX, and HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX. It functions by minimizing or disabling the generation of redo logs, which significantly reduces logging overhead and improves performance, especially during bulk operations and index maintenance tasks. This reduction in redo logging accelerates index creation and rebuild processes. However, the use of NOLOGGING comes with a trade-off: it reduces recoverability because less redo information is available for recovery in the event of a failure. Therefore, employing NOLOGGING requires careful backup and recovery planning to ensure data integrity while benefiting from faster index operations.&lt;SEP&gt;NOLOGGING is a storage option applied to the HR.JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX index that disables redo log generation during index creation and maintenance, improving performance but requiring careful recovery considerations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9070e7e4419dc8073973608dc7299e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f3a649840d8c0d19c4f0b28731832a5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b70313252212b24335f3373f61fa80d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-799db255698d9ddf0d4c7649135906d0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913721</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOCOMPRESS">
      <data key="d0">NOCOMPRESS</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">NOCOMPRESS is a database index storage option that disables data compression for the index, resulting in index entries being stored in an uncompressed form. This approach prioritizes performance by avoiding the CPU overhead associated with compressing and decompressing data, thereby optimizing access speed and improving write performance. While using NOCOMPRESS leads to increased storage usage due to the lack of compression, it is beneficial in scenarios where faster data access and reduced CPU overhead outweigh the cost of additional storage. Examples of indexes utilizing the NOCOMPRESS option include LOC_CITY_IX, hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX, HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX, and HR.JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX, all of which favor performance over storage efficiency by storing their data without compression.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b70313252212b24335f3373f61fa80d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913728</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOPARALLEL">
      <data key="d0">NOPARALLEL</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">NOPARALLEL is a database index configuration option that disables parallel execution of index operations, including creation, maintenance, rebuild, and DML activities. By enforcing serial processing, NOPARALLEL causes these operations to run sequentially rather than concurrently, which can potentially increase maintenance time for large datasets. However, this serial execution helps manage system resources more effectively by reducing resource contention and accommodating specific workload characteristics or environment limitations. NOPARALLEL is applied to various indexes such as HR.JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX, LOC_CITY_IX, hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX, and HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX, where it ensures controlled resource usage and stable performance by preventing parallel processing during index operations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b70313252212b24335f3373f61fa80d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913728</data>
    </node>
    <node id="B-tree Index">
      <data key="d0">B-tree Index</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The B-tree Index is a balanced tree data structure widely used in databases to organize and optimize data retrieval operations. It serves as the default and standard indexing method in various database tables, including HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX, HR.EMP_NAME_IX, HR.EMP_JOB_IX, hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX, JHIST_DEPARTMENT_IX, and LOC_COUNTRY_IX. Characterized by its balanced tree properties, the B-tree Index supports both equality lookups and range queries, enabling efficient range scans, sorting operations, and overall enhanced query performance.

For example, the HR.EMP_JOB_IX utilizes the B-tree structure to improve search performance on the JOB_ID field, while the HR.EMP_NAME_IX and a unique ascending B-tree index on the LAST_NAME and FIRST_NAME columns of the HR.EMPLOYEES table are specifically designed to optimize queries involving employee name lookups and sorting. Additionally, the B-tree Index is implemented as an ascending, non-unique index on COUNTRY_ID in certain contexts, such as the LOC_COUNTRY_IX, further demonstrating its versatility.

Overall, the B-tree Index is a fundamental and effective indexing technique that organizes index entries in a balanced and efficient manner, significantly enhancing data access speed and efficiency across a variety of database tables.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9070e7e4419dc8073973608dc7299e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f9fdf4c76d1900d14f7ab7687630396&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f3a649840d8c0d19c4f0b28731832a5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-799db255698d9ddf0d4c7649135906d0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913510</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR Applications">
      <data key="d0">HR Applications</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">HR Applications are software systems that manage human resources functions such as payroll, team management, and reporting, which utilize the HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX index for performance.&lt;SEP&gt;HR Applications are software systems that utilize the JOB_HISTORY table and its indexes to support human resource management, reporting, and analytics.&lt;SEP&gt;HR Applications are software systems that utilize the HR.EMP_NAME_IX index to perform employee data queries, reporting, and administrative functions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913367</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Reporting Tools">
      <data key="d0">Reporting Tools</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">Reporting Tools are software solutions that access HR data, including JOB_HISTORY and its indexes, to generate reports and analytics for business insights.&lt;SEP&gt;Reporting Tools are software utilities that generate reports from HR data, benefiting from the HR.EMP_NAME_IX index to improve query response times.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913368</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ETL Processes">
      <data key="d0">ETL Processes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes are data integration workflows that use the JOB_HISTORY table and its indexes to extract and transform HR data for analytics and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e98144c173a882faed2108d330b7db66</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912554</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.EMPLOYEES">
      <data key="d0">HR.EMPLOYEES</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.EMPLOYEES is a database table containing employee data, including a DEPARTMENT_ID column linking employees to departments.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.EMPLOYEES is a database table containing employee data, including department identifiers, used in HR business processes.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.EMPLOYEES is a foundational database table within the HR schema that stores comprehensive employee records. It contains detailed information about employees, including unique employee identification, personal details such as LAST_NAME and FIRST_NAME (which are indexed by HR.EMP_NAME_IX to improve query performance), job roles, department assignments, compensation, and hierarchical reporting structures. The table includes a MANAGER_ID column that references employee managers, enabling hierarchical relationships and supporting organizational hierarchy analysis. HR.EMPLOYEES plays a critical role in various human resources functions such as payroll processing and departmental reporting. It also maintains strong referential integrity by being referenced by the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, ensuring that job history entries correspond to valid employees and enforcing multiple foreign key constraints to uphold data consistency across the database.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9070e7e4419dc8073973608dc7299e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f3a649840d8c0d19c4f0b28731832a5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913420</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMPLOYEE_ID">
      <data key="d0">EMPLOYEE_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">EMPLOYEE_ID is a column in the JOB_HISTORY table used to identify employees uniquely, often indexed for efficient querying.&lt;SEP&gt;EMPLOYEE_ID is a key column in the JOB_HISTORY table, representing unique identifiers for employees and used as the indexed column in HR.JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX.&lt;SEP&gt;EMPLOYEE_ID is a numeric unique identifier that serves as the primary key in the HR.EMPLOYEES table, uniquely distinguishing each employee and ensuring data integrity. Additionally, EMPLOYEE_ID functions as a foreign key in the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, where it is part of a composite primary key, maintaining referential integrity between HR.JOB_HISTORY and HR.EMPLOYEES.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-37aec452f877d0a9f13557a9709c0553&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913721</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIRST_NAME">
      <data key="d0">FIRST_NAME</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">FIRST_NAME represents the first name of an employee, intended to be a mandatory field for identification, though the database allows null values.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LAST_NAME">
      <data key="d0">LAST_NAME</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">LAST_NAME is the last name of an employee, a mandatory field used for identification and communication.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMAIL">
      <data key="d0">EMAIL</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">EMAIL is an employee contact attribute in HR.EMPLOYEES, uniquely constrained to prevent duplicates and used for login credentials.&lt;SEP&gt;EMAIL is the unique email address of an employee, used for communication and login credentials, enforced to be unique and not null.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PHONE_NUMBER">
      <data key="d0">PHONE_NUMBER</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">PHONE_NUMBER is the contact number of an employee, including country and area codes, and is an optional field.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HIRE_DATE">
      <data key="d0">HIRE_DATE</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HIRE_DATE records the date when an employee started their current job, important for tenure and payroll calculations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JOB_ID">
      <data key="d0">JOB_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JOB_ID is a key identifier used within the HR schema to represent job roles or positions assigned to employees. It serves multiple purposes across different tables: in the HR.JOBS table, JOB_ID is the primary key column, uniquely identifying each job role with a VARCHAR2(10 BYTE) data type, and it enforces uniqueness and non-nullability. In the EMPLOYEES table, JOB_ID is a column that typically acts as a foreign key referencing the HR.JOBS table, linking employees to their assigned job roles. Similarly, in the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, JOB_ID functions as a mandatory foreign key to the HR.JOBS.JOB_ID column, ensuring valid and consistent job assignments over time. Both the EMPLOYEES and JOB_HISTORY tables have indexes—HR.EMP_JOB_IX and JHIST_JOB_IX respectively—on the JOB_ID column to optimize query performance related to job roles and their associated definitions and responsibilities. Overall, JOB_ID is a varchar identifier that maintains the integrity and consistency of job role data across the HR database.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-af654ef872447926942a03d22d7c2936&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913665</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SALARY">
      <data key="d0">SALARY</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">SALARY represents the monthly salary amount of an employee, which must be greater than zero and is critical for payroll and budgeting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912620</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMISSION_PCT">
      <data key="d0">COMMISSION_PCT</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">COMMISSION_PCT is the commission percentage applicable to employees in the sales department, used for calculating variable compensation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912620</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANAGER_ID">
      <data key="d0">MANAGER_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">MANAGER_ID is a column in the HR.EMPLOYEES table representing the identifier of an employee's manager, used to establish hierarchical relationships.&lt;SEP&gt;MANAGER_ID is a column in the HR.EMPLOYEES table that stores identifiers of employees' managers, enabling self-referential hierarchical relationships among employees.&lt;SEP&gt;MANAGER_ID is a numeric field (NUMBER(6)) that serves as a foreign key in both the HR.DEPARTMENTS and HR.EMPLOYEES tables, playing a crucial role in maintaining organizational structure and hierarchy. In the HR.DEPARTMENTS table, MANAGER_ID references a valid employee as the manager responsible for the department, ensuring organizational consistency; this field is nullable to accommodate departments without assigned managers. In the HR.EMPLOYEES table, MANAGER_ID is a self-referencing foreign key that identifies the manager of an employee, enabling the creation of hierarchical organizational charts and reporting structures by linking employees to their respective managers.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9070e7e4419dc8073973608dc7299e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df7f1caa97c6b4dd058dd6c5d8c8cc76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
