    <node id="Primary Key Constraint">
      <data key="d0">Primary Key Constraint</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The Primary Key Constraint is a database constraint that enforces both uniqueness and non-nullability on a column or a set of columns within a table. It ensures the unique identification of records, which is critical for maintaining data integrity and enabling efficient data lookups. Examples of primary key constraints include the COUNTRY_ID column in the HR.COUNTRIES table, the LOCATION_ID column in the LOCATIONS table, the EMPLOYEE_ID column in the HR.EMPLOYEES table, and the DEPARTMENT_ID column in the DEPARTMENTS table. Additionally, primary key constraints prevent updates to key columns such as COUNTRY_ID, thereby preserving the consistency and reliability of the database.&lt;SEP&gt;The Primary Key Constraint on JOB_ID (named JOB_ID_PK) enforces uniqueness and non-nullability of the JOB_ID column, ensuring each job record is uniquely identifiable.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32be534f99a9a53fb69794f282e09f45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1164983175b10bbf01dc0af45ebb0360&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913667</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Unique Constraint">
      <data key="d0">Unique Constraint</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Unique Constraint enforces uniqueness of data values, such as EMP_EMAIL_UK ensuring unique email addresses.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912625</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Foreign Key Constraint">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Key Constraint</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A Foreign Key Constraint is a database constraint that enforces referential integrity between tables by ensuring that values in one table correspond to valid entries in another related table. For example, it ensures that REGION_ID in the HR.COUNTRIES table references a valid REGION_ID in the HR.REGIONS table, and that COUNTRY_ID values in the LOCATIONS table correspond to valid entries in the COUNTRIES table. Additionally, foreign key constraints maintain consistency of related data, such as linking employees to departments through constraints like EMP_DEPT_FK. Overall, Foreign Key Constraints play a crucial role in maintaining data integrity and consistency across related tables in a database.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1164983175b10bbf01dc0af45ebb0360&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32be534f99a9a53fb69794f282e09f45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec5fba35ba0e1ea8c8f5b0c89a38d27d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913597</data>
    </node>
