    <node id="Hr Schema">
      <data key="d0">Hr Schema</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The HR schema is a database schema that contains tables and objects related to human resources management, including the REGIONS table for geographic classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912756</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.REGIONS Table">
      <data key="d0">HR.REGIONS Table</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The HR.REGIONS table contains geographic region data and must be populated before inserting countries with REGION_ID, ensuring referential integrity within the HR schema.&lt;SEP&gt;The HR.REGIONS table is a core reference table within the HR schema that defines geographic regions. It includes a unique numeric identifier and an optional region name, supports hierarchical location data management, enforces primary key constraints for data integrity, and is designed for efficient querying and integration with related geographic tables. It also supports logging for data recovery and auditing.&lt;SEP&gt;The HR.REGIONS table is a master reference table within the HR schema that stores information about geographic regions. It contains unique region identifiers and optional region names, serving as a foundational entity for geographic classification in HR-related business processes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
