    </node>
    <node id="REGION_NAME">
      <data key="d0">REGION_NAME</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">REGION_NAME is a column in the HR.REGIONS table that stores the names of geographic regions. It is nullable and typically contains human-readable region names used for classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912756</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR Schema">
      <data key="d0">HR Schema</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The HR Schema is a comprehensive database schema designed to store, organize, and manage human resources information within a structured and integrated framework. It serves as a logical container within the database that includes a variety of HR-related tables and objects essential for supporting enterprise HR applications and workflows. Key tables within the HR Schema include HR.EMPLOYEES, HR.DEPARTMENTS, HR.LOCATIONS, HR.JOB_HISTORY, HR.JOBS, HR.COUNTRIES, and HR.REGIONS. These tables collectively manage employee details, job roles, job history, departmental information, and geographic classifications. In addition to these tables, the HR Schema contains several indexes such as HR.EMP_NAME_IX, HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX, HR.EMP_JOB_IX, HR.EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX, and JHIST_JOB_IX, which enhance the efficient organization and access to the human resources data. Overall, the HR Schema is a vital database structure that supports the management of essential human resources data and facilitates effective organizational data management.&lt;SEP&gt;The HR schema is a database schema that contains HR-related tables, including the HR.JOBS table. It manages storage parameters and organizational data structures for human resources.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-af654ef872447926942a03d22d7c2936&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32be534f99a9a53fb69794f282e09f45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913667</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Geographic Regions">
      <data key="d0">Geographic Regions</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">Geographic Regions refer to the hierarchical location data managed and classified within the HR.REGIONS table to support HR business processes.&lt;SEP&gt;Geographic regions are distinct areas defined within the HR.REGIONS table, used to categorize and group locations and countries for hierarchical geographic classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912759</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Countries">
      <data key="d0">Countries</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">Countries are geographic entities that are associated with regions in the HR schema, typically linked via foreign keys to the REGIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912759</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Locations">
      <data key="d0">Locations</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">Locations are specific geographic points or areas that are grouped under countries and regions within the HR schema, supporting detailed geographic classification.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912759</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Primary Key Constraint REG_ID_PK">
      <data key="d0">Primary Key Constraint REG_ID_PK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">REG_ID_PK is the primary key constraint on the REGION_ID column in the HR.REGIONS table, enforcing uniqueness and non-nullability for region identifiers.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912759</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hierarchical Geographic Classification">
      <data key="d0">Hierarchical Geographic Classification</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Hierarchical geographic classification is the method of organizing geographic data in layers, such as regions containing countries, which in turn contain locations, used in the HR schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912759</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Data Integrity">
      <data key="d0">Data Integrity</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Data Integrity refers to the accuracy and consistency of data within a database. In the context of the HR schema, data integrity is maintained through primary and foreign key constraints, which ensure valid and consistent data in tables such as HR.DEPARTMENTS and HR.REGIONS. These constraints enforce the correctness of relationships between tables, thereby preserving data accuracy. Additionally, indexes like LOC_COUNTRY_IX support database performance by enabling efficient enforcement of foreign key constraints, although the index itself does not directly enforce data integrity. Overall, data integrity is upheld by a combination of key constraints and supporting indexes that facilitate reliable and consistent data management.&lt;SEP&gt;Data integrity refers to the accuracy and consistency of data within the HR schema, maintained through constraints such as primary and foreign keys.&lt;SEP&gt;Data integrity ensures the accuracy and consistency of data stored in a database over its lifecycle.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-37aec452f877d0a9f13557a9709c0553&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f9fdf4c76d1900d14f7ab7687630396&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913731</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Performance Optimization">
      <data key="d0">Performance Optimization</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Performance Optimization refers to techniques and configurations aimed at improving system efficiency and speed. In the context of database management, Performance Optimization is the primary business rationale for creating specific indexes such as the hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX index, which enhances query speed for location-based operations. Similarly, in the HR.REGIONS table, performance optimization is achieved through the use of primary key indexing and logging, which support efficient data retrieval and ensure data durability. Additionally, the LOC_COUNTRY_IX index is specifically designed to optimize query performance for operations involving the COUNTRY_ID column. Together, these measures illustrate how Performance Optimization is implemented to improve the speed and efficiency of data access and processing within the system.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-37aec452f877d0a9f13557a9709c0553&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f9fdf4c76d1900d14f7ab7687630396</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913738</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Data Quality Checks">
      <data key="d0">Data Quality Checks</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Data Quality Checks are procedures recommended for the Region Name attribute to prevent null or inconsistent data entries.&lt;SEP&gt;Data quality checks are recommended practices to ensure that region names in the HR.REGIONS table are consistent and non-null where appropriate.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Foreign Keys">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Keys</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Keys are database constraints not explicitly defined in the HR.JOBS table DDL but typically reference JOB_ID from employee or assignment tables to link employees to their job roles.&lt;SEP&gt;Foreign keys are database constraints that link the HR.REGIONS table to other tables such as COUNTRIES and LOCATIONS, enabling relational integrity.&lt;SEP&gt;Foreign keys are database constraints used in the base tables to maintain referential integrity between employees, departments, jobs, locations, countries, and regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913667</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Dependent Objects">
      <data key="d0">Dependent Objects</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Dependent objects are other tables or database objects that rely on the HR.REGIONS table for geographic classification, such as COUNTRIES and LOCATIONS.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f36c7f7c4e6a172a92fe1ea27e35db14</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Region Name">
      <data key="d0">Region Name</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Region Name is an optional attribute in the HR.REGIONS table representing the name of a geographic region, which requires data quality checks to avoid null or inconsistent entries.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Primary Key">
      <data key="d0">Primary Key</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Primary Key is a database constraint applied to the HR.REGIONS table to ensure uniqueness and data integrity of the region identifiers.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Data Recovery">
      <data key="d0">Data Recovery</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Data Recovery is the process of restoring database objects after failure, which is impacted by the NOLOGGING option used in the index creation.&lt;SEP&gt;Data Recovery refers to the process supported by logging mechanisms in the HR.REGIONS table to restore data in case of failure or corruption.&lt;SEP&gt;Data Recovery refers to the ability to restore data after failures, which can be impacted by the use of NOLOGGING in the HR.EMP_NAME_IX index creation or maintenance.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913367</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Auditing">
      <data key="d0">Auditing</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Auditing is the process of tracking and recording changes or access to the HR.REGIONS table data, supported by logging features.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hierarchical Location Data">
      <data key="d0">Hierarchical Location Data</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Hierarchical Location Data refers to the structured geographic data managed within the HR.REGIONS table to support regional classification and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-70ec50d5fc775abc7249f3133791bd96</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912764</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JHIST_JOB_IX">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_JOB_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_JOB_IX is a database index created to improve query performance on the JOB_ID column within the HR.JOB_HISTORY table, enhancing data retrieval speed and efficiency for job history analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912806</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JOB_HISTORY Table">
      <data key="d0">JOB_HISTORY Table</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JOB_HISTORY Table refers to the HR.JOB_HISTORY base table that stores employee job history data, which is the base table for the JHIST_JOB_IX index.&lt;SEP&gt;The JOB_HISTORY table stores records of employees' past job assignments and related data in HR systems.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-37aec452f877d0a9f13557a9709c0553&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913728</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Index Creation">
      <data key="d0">Index Creation</data>
      <data key="d1">event</data>
      <data key="d2">Index Creation refers to the process of building the JHIST_JOB_IX index on the JOB_ID column to improve query performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Index Creation refers to the process of building the LOC_STATE_PROVINCE_IX index on the STATE_PROVINCE column, involving specific storage and performance options.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912927</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Queries Filtering on JOB_ID">
      <data key="d0">Queries Filtering on JOB_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Queries Filtering on JOB_ID are database queries that filter or join data based on the JOB_ID column, benefiting from the JHIST_JOB_IX index.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR Reporting">
      <data key="d0">HR Reporting</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR Reporting involves business processes and applications that analyze employee job history data, relying on efficient data retrieval from the JOB_HISTORY table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Employee Job Tracking">
      <data key="d0">Employee Job Tracking</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Employee Job Tracking refers to business processes that monitor and analyze employee job assignments and transitions over time using data from the JOB_HISTORY table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Backup Strategies">
      <data key="d0">Backup Strategies</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Backup Strategies are data protection plans that must consider the NOLOGGING option's impact on recovery when managing the JHIST_JOB_IX index.&lt;SEP&gt;Backup Strategies are important considerations due to the NOLOGGING option, as index creation or rebuild is not fully recoverable via redo logs.&lt;SEP&gt;Backup strategies are planned procedures to ensure data safety and recovery, especially important when using NOLOGGING during index maintenance.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5214e9996fdebc502db15fbc9950f6f7</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913432</data>
    </node>
    <node id="System Resource Management">
      <data key="d0">System Resource Management</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">System Resource Management involves decisions such as disabling parallelism (NOPARALLEL) to control resource usage during index operations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-654140961a0c915ed4f93c4eca2a34d6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Job History Analysis">
      <data key="d0">Job History Analysis</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Job History Analysis refers to the systematic examination of an individual's past employment records to understand career progression, skills, and experience.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-4ea394c5ec050acbadfb16ec5be61ae2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912809</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Reporting">
      <data key="d0">Reporting</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Reporting involves the process of compiling, organizing, and presenting data and information to stakeholders for decision-making and review.&lt;SEP&gt;Reporting refers to generating business reports that often require filtering or grouping data by geographic regions such as states or provinces.&lt;SEP&gt;The activity of generating reports from data, which is supported by the index through efficient geographic segmentation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1d3ed761714af642cb83ced3f86d6fe5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38310d95744bbc5c98b7150c7d4a14b6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4ea394c5ec050acbadfb16ec5be61ae2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912927</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Data Retrieval">
      <data key="d0">Data Retrieval</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Data Retrieval is the process of obtaining relevant data from databases or information systems to support analysis and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-4ea394c5ec050acbadfb16ec5be61ae2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912811</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Organizational Needs">
      <data key="d0">Organizational Needs</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Organizational Needs represent the requirements and priorities of an organization that guide its operations, strategies, and resource allocation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-4ea394c5ec050acbadfb16ec5be61ae2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912811</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.JOBS">
      <data key="d0">HR.JOBS</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.JOBS is a database table listing valid job roles, referenced by HR.JOB_HISTORY to ensure job role consistency.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.JOBS is a database table listing valid job roles, referenced by HR.JOB_HISTORY to link job assignments to specific job roles.&lt;SEP&gt;The HR.JOBS table is a master reference for job positions within an organization, cataloging all job roles along with their associated salary ranges. It is fundamental for human resources management, payroll processing, and organizational role definitions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913662</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">HR.DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.DEPARTMENTS is a database table containing department information, referenced by HR.JOB_HISTORY to associate job assignments with departments.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.DEPARTMENTS is a database table containing department information, referenced by HR.JOB_HISTORY to link job history records to valid departments.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.DEPARTMENTS is a database table representing departments within the organization, referenced by the DEPARTMENT_ID column in HR.EMPLOYEES.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913420</data>
    </node>
    <node id="START_DATE">
      <data key="d0">START_DATE</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">START_DATE is a date field in HR.JOB_HISTORY representing the beginning of a job assignment period for an employee.&lt;SEP&gt;START_DATE is a date field marking the beginning of an employee's job assignment period, part of the composite primary key in HR.JOB_HISTORY, and must be earlier than END_DATE.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912863</data>
    </node>
    <node id="END_DATE">
      <data key="d0">END_DATE</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">END_DATE is a date field in HR.JOB_HISTORY representing the end of a job assignment period for an employee, constrained to be later than START_DATE.&lt;SEP&gt;END_DATE is a date field marking the end of an employee's job assignment period in HR.JOB_HISTORY, required to be later than START_DATE to ensure valid chronological order.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912863</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JHIST_EMP_ID_ST_DATE_PK">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_EMP_ID_ST_DATE_PK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_EMP_ID_ST_DATE_PK is the composite primary key constraint on HR.JOB_HISTORY, ensuring uniqueness of job history records per employee and start date.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912870</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JHIST_DATE_INTERVAL">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_DATE_INTERVAL</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_DATE_INTERVAL is a check constraint on HR.JOB_HISTORY enforcing that END_DATE must be greater than START_DATE to maintain valid chronological order.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912870</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JHIST_EMP_FK">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_EMP_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_EMP_FK is a foreign key constraint in HR.JOB_HISTORY that references EMPLOYEE_ID in HR.EMPLOYEES to maintain referential integrity.&lt;SEP&gt;JHIST_EMP_FK is a foreign key constraint linking EMPLOYEE_ID in HR.JOB_HISTORY to HR.EMPLOYEES.EMPLOYEE_ID, maintaining referential integrity to employees.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912870</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JHIST_JOB_FK">
      <data key="d0">JHIST_JOB_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JHIST_JOB_FK is a foreign key constraint in HR.JOB_HISTORY that references JOB_ID in HR.JOBS to ensure job role validity.&lt;SEP&gt;JHIST_JOB_FK is a foreign key constraint linking JOB_ID in HR.JOB_HISTORY to HR.JOBS.JOB_ID, ensuring job history entries reference valid job roles.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6c187f531b2027607e34d96862df8d99&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121281388b7802bd6c53e774f27760d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
