    </node>
    <node id="Department">
      <data key="d0">Department</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A department is an organizational unit within a company, identified by department ID and name, associated with a specific location.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912990</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Job Role">
      <data key="d0">Job Role</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A job role defines the position or title held by an employee, described by job ID and job title.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912990</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Location">
      <data key="d0">Location</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A location represents the physical place where a department operates, characterized by city, state or province, and linked to a country.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912990</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Country">
      <data key="d0">Country</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">A country is a geopolitical entity identified by country ID and name, associated with a region and containing multiple locations.&lt;SEP&gt;Country refers to the geographical entities represented by the COUNTRY_ID column in the hr.LOCATIONS table, used for filtering and joining data.&lt;SEP&gt;Country refers to geographic entities identified and standardized within the HR.COUNTRIES table, linked to regions for classification purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-799db255698d9ddf0d4c7649135906d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913597</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Region">
      <data key="d0">Region</data>
      <data key="d1">geo</data>
      <data key="d2">A region is a higher-level geographic area encompassing multiple countries, identified by region name.&lt;SEP&gt;Region represents geographic areas used to classify countries within the HR schema, maintained in the HR.REGIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-9065b661548e2fda446d88c1a5d4a9b7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7bffbbc9cb2999db53c7a202e9b176d4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913600</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Primary Keys">
      <data key="d0">Primary Keys</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Primary keys are unique identifiers in the base tables that ensure each record is uniquely identifiable, supporting data integrity in the HR schema.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Referential Integrity">
      <data key="d0">Referential Integrity</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">A database principle ensuring that foreign key values in HR.COUNTRIES (REGION_ID) correspond to existing primary key values in HR.REGIONS, maintaining data consistency.&lt;SEP&gt;Referential Integrity is maintained through foreign key constraints linking DEPARTMENTS to EMPLOYEES and LOCATIONS tables, ensuring data consistency.&lt;SEP&gt;Referential integrity is a business rule enforced at the database level through foreign keys to ensure valid references among departments, jobs, locations, countries, and regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32be534f99a9a53fb69794f282e09f45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913590</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Read-Only Interface">
      <data key="d0">Read-Only Interface</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The read-only interface is a security feature of the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW that prevents data modification through the view, ensuring data consistency and protection.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Database Privileges">
      <data key="d0">Database Privileges</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Database privileges control access to the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW, restricting who can query the view to protect sensitive employee data.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Indexes">
      <data key="d0">Indexes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Indexes on foreign key columns in base tables improve query performance by optimizing join operations in the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Payroll Systems">
      <data key="d0">Payroll Systems</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Payroll systems are applications or processes that manage employee compensation, which reference the HR.JOBS table for salary and job role information.&lt;SEP&gt;Payroll systems are business processes that utilize the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW to support employee salary and compensation management.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-af654ef872447926942a03d22d7c2936&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913669</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Organizational Hierarchy Analysis">
      <data key="d0">Organizational Hierarchy Analysis</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Organizational hierarchy analysis is a business process supported by the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW using hierarchical queries based on manager relationships.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Location-Based Employee Distribution Reports">
      <data key="d0">Location-Based Employee Distribution Reports</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">These reports use the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW to analyze employee distribution across geographic locations, departments, and regions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Manager ID">
      <data key="d0">Manager ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Manager ID is a key attribute used in hierarchical queries within the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW to build organizational charts and analyze reporting structures.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912995</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Query Performance">
      <data key="d0">Query Performance</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Query Performance refers to the efficiency and speed with which database queries are executed, a critical factor for business processes relying on timely data access. In the context of the HR database, query performance is enhanced by specific indexes such as the HR.EMP_NAME_IX index, which improves operations involving employee names, and the HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX index, which optimizes filtering or joining on the MANAGER_ID field. Additionally, query performance is influenced by factors such as indexing and data volume when executing queries against views like HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW. Overall, effective indexing and data management are key to maintaining high query performance in the HR database environment.&lt;SEP&gt;Query performance refers to the speed and efficiency with which database queries are executed.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-37aec452f877d0a9f13557a9709c0553&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913731</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WITH READ ONLY Clause">
      <data key="d0">WITH READ ONLY Clause</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The WITH READ ONLY clause is a special database feature applied to the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW to prevent DML operations through the view.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912995</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Logging and Auditing">
      <data key="d0">Logging and Auditing</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Logging and auditing track changes at the base table level, ensuring accountability and traceability of data modifications underlying the HR.EMP_DETAILS_VIEW.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-cc669b8fd76a2bbd4d405cb958121319</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753912995</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.EMP_JOB_IX">
      <data key="d0">HR.EMP_JOB_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.EMP_JOB_IX is a non-unique, ascending B-tree index on the JOB_ID column of the EMPLOYEES table in the HR schema. It is designed to improve query performance for job-related employee lookups by optimizing filtering and sorting operations on JOB_ID. The index uses NOLOGGING to reduce redo logging during maintenance, NOCOMPRESS to avoid compression overhead, and NOPARALLEL to disable parallel operations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913034</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMPLOYEES">
      <data key="d0">EMPLOYEES</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">EMPLOYEES is a database table within the HR schema that stores employee data, including job roles identified by the JOB_ID column. It is the table indexed by HR.EMP_JOB_IX to enhance query performance.&lt;SEP&gt;EMPLOYEES is an organizational entity referenced by the HR.DEPARTMENTS table to retrieve manager details and assign employees to departments.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913150</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMPLOYEES Table">
      <data key="d0">EMPLOYEES Table</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">The EMPLOYEES table is a database table within the HR schema that stores comprehensive employee data. It includes employee identifiers, such as EMPLOYEE_ID, which are referenced by other tables like JOB_HISTORY and DEPARTMENTS for tracking job history and managerial assignments, respectively. The table also contains job role information identified by the JOB_ID column, which is used to join with the HR.JOBS table to associate employees with their specific job roles. To enhance query performance for job-related lookups, the EMPLOYEES table is indexed by HR.EMP_JOB_IX. Overall, the EMPLOYEES table serves as a central repository for employee details and their job-related information within the HR database.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-af654ef872447926942a03d22d7c2936&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913728</data>
    </node>
    <node id="JOB_ID Column">
      <data key="d0">JOB_ID Column</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">JOB_ID is a column in the EMPLOYEES table representing the job role or position assigned to an employee. It is typically a foreign key referencing a JOBS or similar lookup table and is the indexed column in HR.EMP_JOB_IX.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913034</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Queries, Views, and Stored Procedures">
      <data key="d0">Queries, Views, and Stored Procedures</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Queries, views, and stored procedures are database objects that interact with the EMPLOYEES table and benefit from the HR.EMP_JOB_IX index when filtering or joining on JOB_ID.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Workforce Management">
      <data key="d0">Workforce Management</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Workforce Management refers to HR business processes involving employee job assignments, reporting, and analytics, supported by efficient data retrieval through the HR.EMP_JOB_IX index.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Payroll Processing">
      <data key="d0">Payroll Processing</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Payroll Processing is an HR business process that involves calculating and managing employee compensation, which relies on accurate and efficient access to job role data.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Organizational Reporting">
      <data key="d0">Organizational Reporting</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Organizational Reporting involves generating reports on employee roles and structure within a company, facilitated by fast queries on job-related data.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Index Maintenance Operations">
      <data key="d0">Index Maintenance Operations</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Index Maintenance Operations include creation, rebuild, and monitoring of the HR.EMP_JOB_IX index, with considerations for NOLOGGING implications and disabled parallelism.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Job Roles">
      <data key="d0">Job Roles</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Job Roles represent the positions or functions assigned to employees, identified by JOB_ID and referenced in HR systems for various HR processes.&lt;SEP&gt;Job roles represent the different positions or classifications within an organization, defined uniquely in the HR.JOBS table and used in HR workflows such as job classification, salary planning, and employee role assignment.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-af654ef872447926942a03d22d7c2936&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e42903e2d1a7030be4f48d545c2a231a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913669</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR Business Processes">
      <data key="d0">HR Business Processes</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR Business Processes encompass a range of structured activities and workflows within human resources aimed at efficiently managing employee-related information and operations. These processes include employee directory lookups, reporting, data validation, employee management by department, payroll processing, and organizational analysis. They rely heavily on efficient access to employee name data, supported by indexes such as the HR.EMP_NAME_IX and the B-tree index on HR.EMPLOYEES, as well as on department-based queries to facilitate accurate and timely human resources functions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-de63f99d53b08ae50d0a514c85b6afd2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7c88e676a8afc774890f3b5fe6b5e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f3a649840d8c0d19c4f0b28731832a5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913431</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Employee Job Data">
      <data key="d0">Employee Job Data</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Employee Job Data encompasses the information related to employees' roles, responsibilities, positions, and employment details within an organization.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-de63f99d53b08ae50d0a514c85b6afd2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913041</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR">
      <data key="d0">HR</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">HR is the database schema that contains the JOB_HISTORY table and the JHIST_EMPLOYEE_IX index, representing the human resources domain.&lt;SEP&gt;HR is the schema or organizational unit responsible for human resources data, including job roles and employee information.&lt;SEP&gt;Human Resources (HR) refers to the organizational function focused on managing employee-related processes, including recruitment, training, payroll, and employee data management.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-de63f99d53b08ae50d0a514c85b6afd2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-711d8bcdc23c815a60cb46edd6c7c69e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913721</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Job Data">
      <data key="d0">Job Data</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Job Data includes detailed information about an employee's role, position, responsibilities, and employment status within an organization.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-de63f99d53b08ae50d0a514c85b6afd2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913041</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Access">
      <data key="d0">Access</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Access refers to the ability or permission to retrieve or use data or resources within an organizational system.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-de63f99d53b08ae50d0a514c85b6afd2</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913041</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPARTMENTS Table">
      <data key="d0">DEPARTMENTS Table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The DEPARTMENTS table is a core organizational structure component within the HR schema, storing information about various company departments including unique identifiers, names, managerial assignments, and physical locations. It supports organizational hierarchy, employee assignment, budgeting, resource allocation, and reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913142</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPARTMENT_NAME">
      <data key="d0">DEPARTMENT_NAME</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPARTMENT_NAME is a mandatory column in the HR.DEPARTMENTS table that provides the name of each department, essential for identification and description.&lt;SEP&gt;DEPARTMENT_NAME is a string field (VARCHAR2(30 BYTE)) representing the name of the department, such as Administration, Marketing, Purchasing, Human Resources, Shipping, IT, Executive, Public Relations, Sales, Finance, and Accounting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913142</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPT_ID_PK">
      <data key="d0">DEPT_ID_PK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPT_ID_PK is the primary key constraint on the DEPARTMENT_ID column in the DEPARTMENTS table, ensuring unique identification of each department.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913147</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPT_MGR_FK">
      <data key="d0">DEPT_MGR_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPT_MGR_FK is a foreign key constraint on the MANAGER_ID column in the DEPARTMENTS table, referencing EMPLOYEES.EMPLOYEE_ID. It enforces that the manager assigned to a department exists as an employee.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913147</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DEPT_LOC_FK">
      <data key="d0">DEPT_LOC_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">DEPT_LOC_FK is a foreign key constraint on the LOCATION_ID column in the DEPARTMENTS table, referencing LOCATIONS.LOCATION_ID. It ensures that the department's location is valid and exists in the LOCATIONS table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913147</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hierarchical Relationships">
      <data key="d0">Hierarchical Relationships</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Hierarchical Relationships describe the bidirectional links where departments reference managers (employees) and employees may reference departments they manage, supporting organizational modeling.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-852dbb615191c11928edcccd02fc0463</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913150</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.DEPARTMENTS Table">
      <data key="d0">HR.DEPARTMENTS Table</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">The HR.DEPARTMENTS table is a foundational organizational table within the HR schema that stores department identifiers, names, managerial assignments, and locations. It enforces data integrity through primary and foreign key constraints and supports hierarchical and location-based relationships.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913150</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_MGR_FK">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_MGR_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_MGR_FK enforces that MANAGER_ID in HR.DEPARTMENTS references a valid employee, maintaining organizational consistency.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913150</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_LOC_FK">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_LOC_FK</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Key Constraint DEPT_LOC_FK enforces that LOCATION_ID in HR.DEPARTMENTS references a valid location, supporting accurate location-based data.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOT NULL Constraint">
      <data key="d0">NOT NULL Constraint</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">NOT NULL Constraints on DEPARTMENT_ID and DEPARTMENT_NAME ensure these fields are mandatory, reflecting their essential role in identifying and describing departments.&lt;SEP&gt;NOT NULL Constraints on JOB_ID and JOB_TITLE columns ensure that these fields must always have values, maintaining data completeness and integrity.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913667</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Nullable Columns">
      <data key="d0">Nullable Columns</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Nullable Columns MANAGER_ID and LOCATION_ID allow flexibility for departments without assigned managers or locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="LOGGING Feature">
      <data key="d0">LOGGING Feature</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">LOGGING enabled on the HR.DEPARTMENTS table ensures all changes are recorded in redo logs for recovery and auditing.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Index on DEPARTMENT_ID">
      <data key="d0">Index on DEPARTMENT_ID</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Index created by the primary key on DEPARTMENT_ID optimizes lookups and joins for efficient data access.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR Workflows">
      <data key="d0">HR Workflows</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Business processes within human resources that utilize geographic data from HR.COUNTRIES, including employee location assignment, payroll regionalization, and organizational reporting.&lt;SEP&gt;HR Workflows refer to business processes involving assigning employees to departments, managing managerial hierarchies, and location-based resource planning.&lt;SEP&gt;HR Workflows refer to business processes that utilize the HR.JOBS table for job classification, salary planning, employee role assignment, payroll, recruitment, and organizational reporting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32be534f99a9a53fb69794f282e09f45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-061cc6d701b5ce39b08e08397ede7d18</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913667</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Managerial Hierarchy">
      <data key="d0">Managerial Hierarchy</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Managerial Hierarchy is the organizational structure supported by linking departments to managers via MANAGER_ID.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Location-Based Resource Planning">
      <data key="d0">Location-Based Resource Planning</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Location-Based Resource Planning involves using department location data to plan and report resources effectively.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-1e9ada454ac1183005c56f36d696a2bf</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913153</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX">
      <data key="d0">hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX is a database index object within the hr schema, designed to optimize query performance on the LOCATION_ID column of the hr.DEPARTMENTS table by providing efficient access paths for location-based filtering and sorting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hr.DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">hr.DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">hr.DEPARTMENTS is a database table within the hr schema that stores information about organizational departments, including a LOCATION_ID column that associates departments with specific locations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Queries, Views, Stored Procedures, Applications">
      <data key="d0">Queries, Views, Stored Procedures, Applications</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">These are database objects and applications that depend on the LOC_COUNTRY_IX index to improve performance of queries filtering or joining on COUNTRY_ID.&lt;SEP&gt;These are database objects and applications that utilize the hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX index to improve performance of location-based queries and operations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f9fdf4c76d1900d14f7ab7687630396</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913503</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Foreign Key Relationship">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Key Relationship</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Key Relationship refers to the likely referential integrity constraint between LOCATION_ID in hr.DEPARTMENTS and the LOCATIONS Table, supported by the index.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913215</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Security and Access Controls">
      <data key="d0">Security and Access Controls</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Security and Access Controls are inherited by the index from the base hr.DEPARTMENTS table, governing permissions and data protection.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5cc87664b23138933a8c4a307851a3c6</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913215</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX">
      <data key="d0">Hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX is a non-compressed, single-column ascending B-tree index on the LOCATION_ID column of the hr.DEPARTMENTS table, designed to optimize query performance for location-based department data retrieval.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913217</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Hr.DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">Hr.DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Hr.DEPARTMENTS is a database table containing department data, including location information, which is indexed by Hr.DEPT_LOCATION_IX.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913217</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Parallelism">
      <data key="d0">Parallelism</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Parallelism is a database operation mode that allows multiple processes to execute simultaneously, affecting performance and complexity.&lt;SEP&gt;Parallelism refers to the database feature that allows operations to be executed concurrently; it is disabled in this index to control resource usage.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-799db255698d9ddf0d4c7649135906d0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913515</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Non-Compressed Index">
      <data key="d0">Non-Compressed Index</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Non-compressed index refers to an index that stores data without compression, potentially using more storage but allowing faster access.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913217</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Single-Column Index">
      <data key="d0">Single-Column Index</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Single-column index is an index built on a single column of a database table to improve query performance on that column.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913217</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Ascending Index">
      <data key="d0">Ascending Index</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Ascending index refers to an index where the data is sorted in ascending order to optimize range queries and sorting.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913217</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Resource Usage">
      <data key="d0">Resource Usage</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Resource usage refers to the consumption of system resources such as CPU, memory, and I/O during database operations, managed here by disabling parallelism.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913221</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Query Plans">
      <data key="d0">Query Plans</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Query Plans are execution strategies used by the database engine for SELECT, UPDATE, and DELETE statements involving the DEPARTMENT_ID column, benefiting from the HR.EMP_DEPARTMENT_IX index.&lt;SEP&gt;Query plans are execution strategies generated by the database optimizer to retrieve data efficiently, influenced by index structures and maintenance.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c6a1efa3aade4dbc0431fee65f96b499&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c484da9a0a9ad0591728777ccd6d9bb8</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1753913425</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX">
      <data key="d0">HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX is a B-tree index on the MANAGER_ID column of the HR.EMPLOYEES table, designed to optimize queries retrieving employees by their manager and support hierarchical organizational structures.&lt;SEP&gt;HR.EMP_MANAGER_IX is a non-compressed, non-parallel B-tree index on the MANAGER_ID column of the HR.EMPLOYEES table, designed to optimize queries retrieving employees by their manager and supporting hierarchical organizational structures in HR applications.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-f86e46cc1908ec692fd894457e73ecd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef9070e7e4419dc8073973608dc7299e</data>
